[1] Russia, Stavropol: poultry
Date: Sat 11 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Itar-tass, 11 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://www.itar-tass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=4365482&PageNum=0>

Tests confirm farm birds in Stavropol Territory infected with H5N1
-----------------------------------------------
Tests conducted by a laboratory of the Animal Protection Institute in
the city of Vladimir have confirmed that birds in the Bogoslovskaya
poultry farm in the Stavropol Territory were infected with the
dangerous H5N1 bird flu virus, the territorial Agriculture Ministry
told Itar-Tass on Saturday [11 Mar 2006]. [Map at
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/RS/70/Bogoslovskiy.html>].
More than 70 000 chickens out of 120 000 in the Bogoslovskaya farm
have died; the rest have been killed. Farm work has been halted. The
area and its roads have been disinfected.
The farm is the 5th bird flu outbreak site in the Stavropol
Territory. The other 4 were reported in the Izobilnensky, Shpakovsky
and Neftekumsky districts and near Kislovodsk. All the outbreaks in
poultry yards were promptly brought under control and prevented from
spreading.
However, a sharp fall in demand for poultry products has been
reported, and farmers' losses amount to millions of rubles, the
ministry noted.
Daily chicken sales decreased by 10 times at most markets in the
territory. [Does this mean that the initial decrease has 10-fold
increased?! Clarification is needed. - Mod.AS]
In an attempt to rectify the situation, the prices were reduced
substantially, but people bought even less, thinking that low-quality
products were on sale.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A similar newswire has been provided by Pablo Nart.
Russia's last (5th) update on HPAI was sent to the OIE on 27 Dec 2005
<http://oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_38.HTM#Sec4>.
It presented a summarizing table of all 62 outbreaks in 10 regions
that had been recorded until that date. Stavropol, in south Russia
between the Black and the Caspian seas, was not included at that
time; see
<http://www.oie.int/cartes/TABA18_52RUS1.PDF>.
According to news media, Stavropol initially suffered avian influenza
in the last week of February 2006 (see 20060301.0649). An official
update is anticipated. - Mod.AS]
