[3] Greece, north: swans
Date: Sat 11 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters Alertnet, 11 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/B728738.htm>

Greece says 4 more swans have deadly bird flu
-----------------------------------------------
Greece on Saturday [11 Mar 2006] confirmed 4 more cases of the lethal
H5N1 strain of bird flu in swans found dead near its northern
borders, bringing to 30 its total number of wild fowl known to have
been infected. "(They) were confirmed today [11 Mar 2006] by the EU
lab in London," the Agriculture Ministry said in a statement, adding
that protective measures had already been in place. [As indicated in
20060220.0550, DEFRA began, since 20 Feb 2006, to publish a table
entitled "Avian Influenza Update from VLA." The table, updated on a
daily basis, was meant to provide information on the samples received
for diagnosis at the AI reference lab (VLA-CRL) in Weybridge and
their tests results. That excellent service is not available any
longer. - Mod.AS]
There have been no cases of bird flu identified in Greek farm
poultry, but sales have plummeted, and the government has announced
measures, including state-guaranteed loans, to help farmers.
Wildlife experts say Greece had a high number of migratory birds this
winter [2006] forced south by an unusually severe winter in northern
Europe.
