[5] Hong Kong, precaution re. cats
Date: Sat 11 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua via People's Daily Online, 10 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://english.people.com.cn/200603/10/eng20060310_249460.html>

Roundup: HK scientists urge checks on sick cats for bird flu
-----------------------------------------------
A cat was sent to the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to
Animals (SPCA) in Hong Kong on Wednesday [8 Mar 2006]. It is the only
cat surrendered to the society since reports surfaced of H5N1 virus
infecting cats in Germany, Austria SPCA spokeswoman Rebecca Ngan said
on Thursday [9 Mar 2006].
According to Ngan, the cat brought home a dead bird from the garden
one day, and the owner was pretty scared about that, so she
surrendered the cat. The cat is in good health now, Ngan said.
On Wednesday [8 Mar 2006], Hong Kong scientists urged checks on dead
and sick cats so as to prevent the transmission of H5N1 virus to
humans.
Several cats in Austria and Germany were found with the dangerous
H5N1 virus later, and Dutch scientists have evidence that cats can
spread the virus to one another in the laboratory. Meanwhile, Thai
scientists have found that dogs and cats there also could be carrying
the virus.
University of Hong Kong chair professor of microbiology Yuen
Kwok-yung warned Wednesday [8 Mar 2006] the cat cases showed that
these mammals are vulnerable. He said cats that strayed in villages
in the New Territories of Hong Kong had a higher chance of contact
with bird carcasses, which increased their risk of bird flu.
"Dead or sick cats, which are wandering around in villages outside
people's homes, should be collected for testing," he said.
The Hong Kong Agriculture, Fisheries and Conservation Department said
Wednesday [8 Mar 2006] night that up till now, there is no evidence
that cats could transmit H5N1 to humans. "A recent report from the
World Health Organization indicates that the confirmation of H5N1
infection in cats is not considered likely to enhance the present
risk to human health," a spokesman said. But he advised cat owners
not to allow their pets to eat wild birds.
Paul Chan, a professor of microbiology from the Chinese University of
Hong Kong, said people should not ignore the occurrence of the virus
in felines.
"The infection of cats is not a brand new finding, but there is some
data to suggest that birds can be infected without symptoms. So if
these cats are infected without symptoms, and if they can spread the
virus, this can lead to a very different situation," Chan said.
"We are not sure if (the virus) can spread between cats, but we
better assume it can," he added.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[There are several good reasons for prescribing the maintenance of
domestic cats exclusively inside the home: health-wise (human health,
as well as the cats' own health) and environmental (some wildlife
species, mainly small birds, have been shown to be seriously
endangered by stray and free-roaming released owned cats). Avian
influenza is now added to the factors supporting the prevention of
cat straying; banning the release of owned cats deserves serious
consideration.
See "Bird Flu Fears and New Rules Rattle German Pet Lovers" at
<http://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/05/international/europe/05flu.html>.
- Mod.AS]
